BP, EDP Renovaveis, Reed Elsevier, Shell, Tesco Plc: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-04-19T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/bp-edp-renovaveis-reed-elsevier-shell-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 1.7 percent to 273.05. The
Stoxx 50 Index declined 1.9 percent to 2,562.24. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, slid 2.4
percent to 2,847.96.  AstraZeneca Plc (AZN)  : The second-biggest U.K
drugmaker’s MedImmune unit and a U.K.-financed research agency
were sued by Novartis AG (NOVN VX), seeking to annul a five-year
protection certificate granted for a joint European patent for a
way to make antibody fragments. The shares retreated 2.1 percent
to 2,952.5 pence.  BP Plc (BP/ LN): OAO Rosneft may swap shares with the
British  oil company  and find a new partner for Arctic drilling
if a court allows the U.K. explorer to split the two parts of
their agreement, an independent director at BP’s Russian venture
said. The stock fell 0.9 percent to 451.65 pence.  EDP Renovaveis SA (EDPR)  : The renewable-energy unit of
Portuguese utility EDP-Energias de Portugal SA said first-
quarter power production rose 21 percent as it added wind energy
projects. The shares slumped 2.8 percent to 4.93 euros.  Reed Elsevier NV (REN)  : The owner of the LexisNexis
database and ComputerWeekly magazine is scheduled to give a
trading update before the start of trading.  Reed Elsevier  rose
less than 0.1 percent to 9.04 euros.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s biggest oil
company said it was restarting a unit at its Scotford refinery
in  Alberta  and would flare gases for four to six hours. The
shares fell 2.5 percent to 2,179 pence.  Tesco Plc (TSCO)  : The U.K.’s largest retailer may report
full-year net income of 2.6 billion pounds ($4.2 billion),
according to the average of 17 estimates compiled by Bloomberg.
The shares dropped 1.8 percent to 400 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
